SIMPLE: motion
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Motion
<hw>Mo"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. L.
<ets>motio</ets>, fr. <ets>movere</ets>, <ets>motum</ets>, to move. See
<er>Move</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act, process, or state of
changing place or position; movement; the passing of a body from one
place or position to another, whether voluntary or involuntary; --
opposed to <contr>rest</contr>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Speaking or mute, all comeliness and grace⟦br⟧
attends thee, and each word, each <qex>motion</qex>, forms.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Power of, or capacity for, motion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Devoid of sense and <qex>motion</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Direction of movement; course; tendency; <as>as, the
<ex>motion</ex> of the planets is from west to east</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In our proper <qex>motion</qex> we ascend.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Change in the relative position of the parts of
anything; action of a machine with respect to the relative movement of
its parts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This is the great wheel to which the clock owes its
<qex>motion</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Dr. H. More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Movement of the mind, desires, or passions; mental
act, or impulse to any action; internal activity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let a good man obey every good <qex>motion</qex> rising in his
heart, knowing that every such <qex>motion</qex> proceeds from God.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A proposal or suggestion looking to action or
progress; esp., a formal proposal made in a deliberative assembly;
<as>as, a <ex>motion</ex> to adjourn</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yes, I agree, and thank you for your <qex>motion</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>An application made to a court or
judge orally in open court. Its object is to obtain an order or rule
directing some act to be done in favor of the applicant.</def>
<rj><au>Mozley & W.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>Change of pitch in successive
sounds, whether in the same part or in groups of parts.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The independent <qex>motions</qex> of different parts sounding
together constitute counterpoint.</q> <rj><qau>Grove.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Conjunct motion</xex> is that by single degrees of
the scale. <xex>Contrary motion</xex> is that when parts move in
opposite directions. <xex>Disjunct motion</xex> is motion by skips.
<xex>Oblique motion</xex> is that when one part is stationary while
another moves. <xex>Similar</xex> or <xex>direct motion</xex> is that
when parts move in the same direction.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>A puppet show or puppet.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What <qex>motion</qex>'s this? the model of Nineveh?</q>
<rj><qau>Beau. & Fl.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Motion, in mechanics, may be simple or compound.
<col><b>Simple motions</b></col> are: (<stype>a</stype>) <xex>straight
translation</xex>, which, if of indefinite duration, must be
reciprocating. (<stype>b</stype>) <xex>Simple rotation</xex>, which may
be either continuous or reciprocating, and when reciprocating is called
<xex>oscillating</xex>. (<stype>c</stype>) <xex>Helical</xex>, which, if
of indefinite duration, must be reciprocating. <col><b>Compound
motion</b></col> consists of combinations of any of the simple
motions.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Center of motion</b></col>, <col><b>Harmonic
motion</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See under <er>Center</er>,
<er>Harmonic</er>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Motion block</b></col>
<fld>(Steam Engine)</fld>, <cd>a crosshead.</cd> -- <col><b>Perpetual
motion</b></col> <fld>(Mech.)</fld>, <cd>an incessant motion conceived
to be attainable by a machine supplying its own motive forces
independently of any action from without. According to the law of
conservation of energy, such perpetual motion is impossible, and no
device has yet been built that is capable of perpetual
motion.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Movement</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motion</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Motion
<hw>Mo"tion</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Motioned</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Motioning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make a
significant movement or gesture, as with the hand; <as>as, to
<ex>motion</ex> to one to take a seat</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make proposal; to offer plans.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Motion</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Motion
<hw>Mo"tion</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To direct or invite
by a motion, as of the hand or head; <as>as, to <ex>motion</ex> one to a
seat</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To propose; to move.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I want friends to <qex>motion</qex> such a matter.</q>
<rj><qau>Burton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>motional</ent>⟦br⟧
